  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Discourse on the Hall of Motion
  author: Lee Dal-choong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Attendant White Minister Mun-bo once commanded me to write a discourse on the Hall of Motion, but I have long lacked the courage to do so. Now that you depart as inspector of the eastern provinces, all gentlemen offer their verses, yet my poetry has grown crude since adversity befell me—I cannot give it voice in song. Instead, I offer this discourse on the Hall of Motion as farewell, a mere evening's conversation. I beg the reader's forbearance.

    From motion springs fortune and misfortune, regret and constraint. Even the sages have not ceased to attend to this. Thus we move only when propriety permits, when we discern goodness. In stillness, if we do not nurture the heart with sincerity and reverence, our movements may veer toward restlessness and delusion. How weighty, then, is the timing of motion! The hexagram of Heaven declares: "Heaven moves with vigor; the gentleman thus strengthens himself without ceasing." To move with vigor is motion at its utmost. When the gentleman embodies this, he becomes strong and unceasing. Yet there remains the submergent phase when action serves not, and the exalted phase where regret follows. Thus sometimes one appears in the fields, sometimes leaps into the abyss—trembling, then bracing oneself—only then can one accomplish. Move without right timing, and disaster surely follows. Those who excel at motion must await the moment, must accord with it. The moment is the subtle turning-point. Only the gentleman perceives it and acts.

    Minister White of Jiksan has inscribed his dwelling "Hall of Motion." Is this not a great way of conducting himself? I have heard that the principles of motion and stillness turn as an endless wheel—stillness becomes motion, motion becomes stillness, each the root of the other, with not a hair's breadth between them. One cannot be merely still, nor merely in motion. What then is the Minister's intent in taking motion? Pondering, I cannot fathom it. Thus I inscribed the character upon the wall, and when asked, I say, "The Minister's tablet." Some say, "Perhaps the Minister, being too compassionate and mild, wishes to spur himself toward courage and boldness?" Others say, "To achieve that, one must proceed through this—it is natural. Since the Minister's name grows daily brighter and cannot be hidden, perhaps through motion he seeks stillness?" But this is not so.

    Sit, and I shall tell you. One yin, one yang—this is called the Way. Such is the meaning of motion and stillness. The sage honors the yang and deems the yin base. How can one who aspires to sagehood not know the excellence toward which to strive?

    The Minister's motion—inwardly, he makes his sovereign like Yao; outwardly, his people like Yao's subjects. He unfolds great plans, perfects exquisite governance, never ceasing until the ultimate is reached. What manner of motion is this? Yet even this does not capture the Minister's true motion.

    When he sits in this hall, adjusting his robes and composing his countenance, dwelling in stillness without thought or labor, motionless—people know only his stillness. They do not perceive the stillness within motion that dwells there. The Minister once traversed the realms of Fixation, Stillness, and Peace, wandering through the lands of Great Transformation and Sage-Spirit, dwelling in the house of Utmost Good, seeking how to employ it. One day the ruler sat in the Hall of Radiant Light, summoned the Minister, and asked of the world's affairs. His reply accorded with the ruler's intent. The ruler was greatly pleased, saying, "I shall employ you greatly," and bestowed upon him the Wine of Equilibrium. The Minister drank and grew intoxicated, returning to rest in his hall. Some say, "Heaven has decreed it."
  footnotes:
    - White Minister (白常侍) refers to Yi Dal-choong's contemporary and possibly patron, a high official given the title 'Minister' (常侍).
    - The Hall of Motion (動齋) is both a physical space and a philosophical concept—a chamber dedicated to understanding the principle of timely action.
    - References to the I Ching (Book of Changes) hexagrams and their imagery run throughout, particularly the Heaven (乾) hexagram symbolizing vigorous action.
    - The mention of Yao refers to the legendary sage-king of ancient China, an ideal of virtuous rulership.
    - The "Wine of Equilibrium" (中和之酒) is a symbolic reward representing harmony and balance bestowed by the ruler.
